<section xml:id="investigation1-16">
  <title>Investigation 1.16: Literary Digest</title>

  <p>Literary Digest was a well-respected political magazine founded in 1890. Using sampling, they correctly predicted the presidential outcomes from 1916–1932. In 1936, they conducted the most extensive (to that date) public opinion poll in history. They mailed out questionnaires (postcards) to over 10 million people (about one-fourth of voters), hand addressing more than a quarter million postcards per day) whose names and addresses they obtained from club rosters, city directories, and (mostly) vehicle registration lists and telephone books.</p>

  <p>Based on almost 2.4 million responses (2,376,523), the Literary Digest predicted that 54% of voters would vote for Republican Alf Landon (then governor of Kansas) in the upcoming presidential election, and only 41% would vote for Democrat Franklin Roosevelt (the incumbent).</p>

  <exercise xml:id="I1-16-a">
    <title>Identify study components</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Identify the variable and population of interest, the sample, and the sampling frame in this study. Also define the parameter and statistic, in words and symbols, and indicate any values that you know.</p>
      <p>Variable: <var width="40"/> Type: <var width="20"/></p>
      <p>Population of interest: <var width="40"/> Sample: <var width="40"/></p>
      <p>Sampling frame: <var width="60"/></p>
      <p>Parameter: <var width="60"/></p>
      <p>Statistic: <var width="60"/></p>
    </statement>
    <response/>
    <solution>
      <p>Variable: Presidential vote preference; Type: Categorical (binary)</p>
      <p>Population of interest: All U.S. voters in 1936; Sample: 2,376,523 respondents to the Literary Digest poll</p>
      <p>Sampling frame: People with names/addresses from club rosters, city directories, vehicle registration lists, and telephone books</p>
      <p>Parameter: <m>\pi</m> = proportion of all 1936 voters who would vote for Landon (unknown)</p>
      <p>Statistic: <m>\hat{p}</m> = 0.54, proportion of poll respondents who said they would vote for Landon</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <exercise xml:id="I1-16-b">
    <title>Calculate actual proportion</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Why is <m>1293669/(1293669 + 972897) = 0.57</m> not equal to 0.54?</p>
      <p><var width="60"/></p>
    </statement>
    <response/>
    <solution>
      <p>The 0.57 is the proportion among the two main candidates (Landon and Roosevelt only), while 0.54 includes all candidates in the poll.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <p>Have you ever heard of Alf Landon? He lost. By a landslide. Incumbent Democrat Franklin Roosevelt won the election, carrying 60.8% of the popular vote to Landon's 36.5%.</p>

  <exercise xml:id="I1-16-c">
    <title>Explain polling error</title>
    <statement>
      <p>Give two plausible explanations why the Literary Digest prediction was so much in error. In particular, talk about the direction of the bias – why was this sampling method vulnerable to producing an overestimate of the parameter?</p>
      <p><var width="60"/></p>
    </statement>
    <response/>
    <solution>
      <p>1. The sampling frame (vehicle registration and telephone book lists) excluded poorer Americans who couldn't afford cars or phones, and these voters tended to be Democrats.</p>
      <p>2. Voluntary response bias - those who chose to respond may have been more dissatisfied with the incumbent (Roosevelt) or had more time/resources to complete and mail surveys, potentially overrepresenting Republicans.</p>
    </solution>
  </exercise>

  <p>Still, a 24% response rate is much higher than current polls and this was the Digest's largest poll yet, shouldn't this improve their prediction? How are current polls with smaller response rates and smaller sample sizes able to be more accurate? One reason suggested for the error in 1936 was that the Digest had consistently been having more Republican voters responding to their straw vote. Does the data support this argument?</p>

